snippet.textDisplay: I really enjoyed this video a lot. I would like to point out that the liquid kansui that Yuji uses is indeed an alkali, but is not exactly equivalent to baking soda. Kansui is a mixture of sodium carbonate and potassium carbonate which can be purchased as either a powder or a liquid, but it can be quite tough to procure outside of Asia. I was able to get the powder kansui online from a Japanese retailer, and when making your noodles you use one gram of kansui per 100 grams of flour. Ramen has so many facets I think it is approachable by cooks of all levels of expertise. I think all the chefs did a great job. I look forward to more videos in this series.
snippet.textOriginal: I really enjoyed this video a lot. I would like to point out that the liquid kansui that Yuji uses is indeed an alkali, but is not exactly equivalent to baking soda. I was able to get the powder kansui online from a Japanese retailer, and when making your noodles you use one gram of kansui per 100 grams of flour.
